With Bittensor mining; if for some reason a miner decides they want to leave the network and no longer participate ; does that hurt the network level of intelligence ?

though once the network starts having more custom models being trained to run on it, the network itself can be distilled to train new models that have the knowledge of the network built into them, which can then, themselves, be plugged back into the network

they wont be the top of the line models, but they'll essentially increase the baseline average intelligence in the network

Its not based on PoS or PoW, but based on PoI: Proof of Intelligence. The goal is to lower the loss on AI models.
Are the AI models purely ML?

All AI models are basically ML models, but these ones have a form of "intelligence" on it. I cant get too deep on it without skipping the layman terms, but its a teacher-student type of training, hence the "intelligence" part.
So, the more data fed into the network, the better the models become, and those models can be eventually used in production.
What kind of data is being used on our network up to now? How "high" level is it now as in is it already attractive to companies as a way to improve efficiencies of scale for example?

Well, we have models being served that are bigger as "the pile". The models that the validators produce are basically "distilled" models of the network. You could technically use the network as a giant compute unit and use the destilled model as the base for a chatbot...

Different from other ETH-based networks, this one does not rely on putting data "on the chain", the miners get rewarded for lowering the loss of the validators, and the validators get rewarded for weighing the miners on productivity. In the end, you could have a small model that fits on the phone, with the intelligence that the big servers provide.

For now, if you want to run a GPT-3 sized model, you need to have a big cluster. With the teacher-student training that the network is doing, you could have that same output in the footprint of a GPT-2 model...

Yes that's right. We aren't launching any 
 CEXs until we have proper decentralization and have passed / close to passing the howey decentralization test (legally this also has the benefit of keeping us from being pursued by the SEC for trading as a security). 

The same goes for DEXs too. We aren't interested in listing on anything besides polkadot.

messages.content:
Well, its complicated: We have 3 classes of tax calculations called "boxes". Since its an "asset", its classified as "box 3". Cryptocurrencies are considered to have a "cash" value, so you need to provide the value on the 1st of January (amount * sale price) in box 3. That does also include NFT's and other assets (like gold).
Then you have the "capital gains" from selling the coin. That is "box 1", taxable income. Since i earn a lot from my work, i am already in the highest class of income (52%). I have to classify it as "income from other sources".
